DEVELOPMENT PRINCIPLES

These principles govern every file generated in this project.
Cross-reference them before producing any output.

---

ARCHITECTURE

1. RAE IS A PURE FUNCTION — NEVER VIOLATE THIS.
   lib/rae/engine.ts and all files it calls (surplus.ts, classifier.ts,
   allocator.ts, shock.ts) must have zero database access and zero
   network calls. They receive data as arguments and return results.
   Only app/api/rae/route.ts touches Supabase.

2. SEPARATION OF CONCERNS — ONE FILE, ONE JOB.
   surplus.ts computes surplus only. classifier.ts determines stage only.
   allocator.ts distributes money only. shock.ts applies shock adjustment
   only. engine.ts orchestrates only. Never merge these concerns.

3. SCHEMA FIRST — UI NEVER DRIVES DATA SHAPE.
   The database schema in rail_database_schema.md is the source of truth.
   No TypeScript type, API response shape, or component prop may
   contradict it. If a conflict appears, flag it before generating code.

4. APP ROUTER ONLY — NEVER PAGES ROUTER.
   All Next.js files live in the app/ directory. Never generate files
   in a pages/ directory. Never use getServerSideProps or getStaticProps.

5. SERVER COMPONENTS BY DEFAULT.
   All data fetching happens in server components or API routes.
   Use 'use client' only when the component requires browser APIs,
   user interaction state, or React hooks. Never fetch Supabase data
   in a client component.

---

MONEY

6. ALL MONETARY VALUES ARE INTEGERS IN PENCE — NO EXCEPTIONS.
   £2,800 is stored and computed as 280000. Never use floats for money.
   Never store pounds. Never compute in pounds. Conversion to pounds
   happens only at the display layer: (pence / 100).toFixed(2).

7. PENCE ARITHMETIC ONLY IN THE RAE ENGINE.
   The engine operates exclusively in pence. Display components divide
   by 100. This boundary must never blur.

8. ROUNDING IS EXPLICIT.
   Use Math.round() for all pence-level rounding. After allocation,
   verify: bufferContribution + Σ(debtAllocations) + investmentContribution
   === surplus exactly. If off by 1p, add it to the final term.

---

SECURITY & DATA

9. ROW LEVEL SECURITY ON EVERY TABLE — NO EXCEPTIONS.
   Every Supabase table must have an RLS policy. Never generate a table
   migration without the accompanying RLS policy in the same block.
   Never expose data without auth.uid() gating.

10. SECRETS LIVE IN .env.local — NEVER HARDCODED.
    No API key, URL, or secret value ever appears in application code.
    Always reference process.env.VARIABLE_NAME. If a value is needed
    that doesn't have an environment variable yet, add a placeholder
    and flag it with a // TODO: add to .env.local comment.

11. rae_executions IS IMMUTABLE — NEVER UPDATE OR DELETE.
    This table is an append-only FCA Consumer Duty audit log.
    Never generate UPDATE or DELETE statements targeting it.
    Only INSERT is permitted.

12. NEVER STORE RAW TRUELAYER TOKENS IN THE DATABASE.
    Truelayer access tokens must be held server-side or encrypted.
    Never write a token to a Supabase column directly.

---

TYPESCRIPT

13. STRICT MODE IS DISABLED FOR PHASE 0A — DO NOT ENABLE IT.
    tsconfig.json has "strict": false. This is deliberate. Do not add
    strict: true. Do not suggest enabling it.

14. USE 'any' SPARINGLY AND ALWAYS FLAG IT.
    Only use 'any' when a precise type requires excessive boilerplate.
    Every 'any' must be accompanied by: // TODO: tighten type

15. ALL FILES USE .ts OR .tsx — NEVER .js OR .jsx.
    This is a TypeScript project throughout. Never generate plain
    JavaScript files.

---

DEPENDENCIES & COMPONENTS

16. shadcn/ui IS THE DEFAULT UI PRIMITIVE.
    Always use shadcn/ui components (Card, Button, Badge, Progress, Toast,
    etc.) before building custom components. Only build custom when
    shadcn genuinely cannot provide what is needed.

17. NEVER DEVIATE FROM THE DEFINED TECH STACK WITHOUT FLAGGING IT.
    Stack: Next.js 14, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, Supabase,
    Truelayer, Recharts, Resend, Posthog. If a request would require
    adding a package outside this list, state it explicitly and ask
    before proceeding.

---

CODE QUALITY

18. ALWAYS SHOW THE FULL FILE — NOT JUST THE CHANGED SECTION.
    When modifying a file under 200 lines, show the complete updated file.
    For files over 200 lines, show clearly marked diffs with sufficient
    surrounding context to locate the change.

19. ALWAYS STATE WHAT YOU ARE BUILDING AND WHY BEFORE THE CODE BLOCK.
    One short paragraph before every code block explaining the purpose
    of the file and its role in the architecture.

20. ONE TASK PER COMPOSER SESSION.
    Generate one file or one coherent feature at a time. Do not bundle
    unrelated changes. Each output should be committable as a single
    git commit.

21. IF AMBIGUOUS, STATE YOUR ASSUMPTION AND PROCEED.
    Do not ask multiple clarifying questions before producing output.
    State the assumption clearly at the top of the response, then build.

22. NEVER SUGGEST MONEY MOVEMENT CODE.
    No automated sweeps, scheduled transfers, or background payment
    execution. This prototype is read-only. The RAE recommends.
    The user acts.